The Nigeria Immigration Service (NIS) will on Monday resume the issuance of processed passports as well as fresh enrolments. NIS, in a statement issued yesterday by its spokesman, Sunday James, explained that this was sequel to the federal government’s directive on phased and gradual easing of the lockdown in Lagos and Abuja from Monday, May 4, 2020. Giving a breakdown of the planned exercise, the NIS said that its gates would be opened for immediate collection of cleared passports at its Headquarters in Abuja and all the passport offices nationwide from May 4 to May 15 unless the states that are experiencing complete lockdown in view of their peculiar situation and the state government’s position on COVID-19. James, however, explained that only applicants invited by SMS through their mobile phones were expected to turn up on the scheduled dates. He said that there shall be gradual enrolment for only enhanced passports at the following locations that issues it: Immigration Service Headquarters, Abuja, Ikoyi, Alausa, Kano Main Passport Office and Port Harcourt on May 18, 2020 The NIS spokesman added that beginning from May 25, “all passport offices nationwide are to operate a gradual processing and enrolment with strict compliance with social distancing, wearing of face masks, and use of hand sanitisers. “The whole passport operation should be done in compliance with National Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) standard. All services at our diplomatic and consular missions will be directed by the respective missions based on country situation,” he added. James said that the comptroller-general stressed the need for all passport officers, their staff as well as applicants to comply with NCDC standard to avoid further spread of COVID-19 from person to person.